title: For Sale:  Colt Single Action Army revolver General Patton SAA .45...Engraved/Silver AMERICAN HISTORICAL FOUNDATION
postcontent: Never cocked and never fired! Here's a beautiful copy of the Colt Single Action Army revolver that was carried by one of America's most famous military figures, General George S. Patton. This revolver was commissioned by the American Historical Foundation and is based on a Uberti Single Action revolver that has been elaborately hand engraved and silver plated, just like the original. Chambered for the .45 Colt cartridge and wearing a 4-3/4" barrel, this is a fully functional firearm, not just a work of art. The imitation ivory grips have special medallions indicating the years of Patton's birth and passing. The right panel is scrimshawed with the General's initials, just like the original. Condition is perfect with the exception of some slight tarnish to the silver in the protected spots which would easily polish bright if desired. There is no rust, pitting, or handling wear. The revolver was zip-tied at the factory and remains so...never cocked. It comes in a very high quality glass sided display case that allows the gun to be displayed on a shelf or table top and viewed from either side.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Israel K98, .308 Excellent Condition. Crest left intact. Tight action!
postcontent:
This rifle was re-arsenaled by Fabrique Nationale d'Herstal (FN). The action was originally a vz-24. The crest is still left intact on top of the receiver; im not going to squawk the word "rare" all over like others, but this was very uncommon due to the Israelis commonly buffed of the original markings and replaced it with their own. There is a buff mark on the side of the receiver where the Israelis implemented their serial number system. The action, bolt, and barrel serials match. The barrel, bore, and action are in excellent condition. The action is one of the tightest I have felt. The stock does not match, the stocks were made of beech wood, hence why the stock isnt the prettiest. Likely replaced by the Israelis. The stock is very smooth with only a few nicks and dings from use. The stock hardware; barrel bands, and but plate are loosing their finish as you can see, a common occurrence.

Listing to see whats out their, only trades would be a quality semi-auto, or bolt rifle. Mini-30, sako or tikka bolt action, ruger, maybe nice rem 700 or 798.

Price is firm!
